## 1. Getting Started with Tor Browser

### 1.1. First Launch

**Initial Configuration:**
```
1. Start Tor Browser
2. Connection options:
   ├─ "Connect" - Direct connection (most common)
   ├─ "Configure" - Proxy/VPN settings
   └─ "Censored" - Bridge configuration
```

**Connection Verification:**
- Visit: `check.torproject.org`
- Expected result: "Congratulations. This browser is configured to use Tor."
- Displays assigned IP address (different from your real IP)

### 1.2. Understanding the Interface

#### 1.2.1. Key Elements

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ 🧅 Tor Browser │ Search or enter address  │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                             │
│                                             │
│            Main browsing area               │
│                                             │
│                                             │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
Security Level: Standard | Safer | Safest
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**The Onion Menu (🧅):**
- **New Identity**: Clears all data, creates new Tor circuit
- **New Tor Circuit for this Site**: Changes nodes for current site
- **Onion Circuits**: View current node chain
- **Security Settings**: Adjust protection level
- **Tor Network Settings**: Configure bridges/proxies

### 1.3. Security Settings Explained

#### 1.3.1. Level: Standard
```javascript
✓ All JavaScript enabled
✓ Media auto-plays
✓ NoScript disabled
✓ Best compatibility
Risk: Higher tracking potential
```

#### 1.3.2. Level: Safer (Recommended)
```javascript
✗ JavaScript disabled on HTTP sites
✗ Media click-to-play
✓ NoScript enabled (selective)
✓ HTTPS sites mostly functional
Risk: Moderate tracking protection
```

#### 1.3.3. Level: Safest
```javascript
✗ JavaScript disabled everywhere
✗ All media click-to-play
✗ Performance optimizations disabled
✗ Many sites may break
Risk: Minimal tracking, maximum security
```

**Changing Security Level:**
1. Click onion icon (🧅)
2. Select "Security Settings"
3. Choose desired level
4. Restart browser if prompted

## 2. Deep Web Search Engines

### 2.1. Ahmia (Recommended)

**URL:** `https://ahmia.fi` (also accessible via Tor)

**Best For:**
- General deep web searching
- Finding active "onion" sites
- Clean, fast results

**Features:**
- Sorts results by relevance
- Shows site age/status
- Displays response time
- Statistics panel
- I2P search option

**Usage Example:**
```
Search: "privacy guides"
Results:
├─ 0.05 seconds
├─ Relevance sorting
├─ Site status indicators
└─ Direct "onion" links
```

### 2.2. Candle

**URL:** `http://candleabrajp5jtrh2"onion"` (Tor only)

**Best For:**
- Minimalist interface
- Recent content discovery
- Google-like experience

**Features:**
- Black theme (easy on eyes)
- Sorts by last modified date
- Pagination support
- Description snippets

**Comparison:**
| Feature | Ahmia | Candle |
|---------|-------|--------|
| Sorting | Relevance | Recency |
| Interface | Modern | Minimalist |
| Index Size | Large | Medium |
| Speed | Fast | Fast |

### 2.3. Not Evil

**Best For:**
- Alternative indexing
- Simple searches

**Search Options:**
- Search by title only
- Search by URL
- Search both

**Note:** Results may include foreign language sites (Russian common)

### 2.4. Grams

**Best For:**
- Market searches
- Product discovery
- Vendor information

**Features:**
- Market-specific results
- Vendor ratings
- Price information
- Bitcoin amounts shown

**Usage:**
- Filter by cryptocurrency
- View vendor trust levels
- See product availability

### 2.5. Torch

**Best For:**
- Large archive searches
- Older content

**Limitations:**
- Many dead links
- Older index
- Less reliable than Ahmia/Candle

## 3. Anonymous Email Services

### 3.1. ProtonMail

**Access:** Clear web + Dark web

**Features:**
- End-to-end encryption
- Zero-access encryption (ProtonMail can't read emails)
- Swiss privacy laws
- No logs policy
- Open source

**Account Tiers:**
```
Free:
├─ 500MB storage
├─ 150 messages/day
└─ Limited features

Plus ($5/month):
├─ 5GB storage
├─ 1000 messages/day
├─ Custom domains
└─ Advanced features
```

**Setup via Tor:**
1. Visit protonmail.com through Tor Browser
2. Click "Sign Up"
3. Select free plan
4. Create username and password
5. **Optional:** Add recovery email (compromises anonymity)
6. Complete CAPTCHA
7. Account ready

### 3.2. TorBox

**Access:** Tor only ("onion")

**Features:**
- No clear web connection
- All traffic through Tor
- Simple interface
- No frills, basic email

**Setup:**
```
1. Visit TorBox "onion" address
2. Select "Sign Up"
3. Enter username
4. Create password
5. Confirm password
6. Complete CAPTCHA
7. Mailbox ready
```

**Technical Details:**
- Server-to-MTA encryption
- Webmail via SquirrelMail
- No advanced features
- Perfect for basic anonymous communication

### 3.3. Bitmessage

**Access:** Gateway service (requires Bitmessage client)

**Features:**
- Decentralized messaging
- No central servers
- Proof-of-work anti-spam
- Encrypted by default

**Setup Process:**
```
1. Download Bitmessage client
2. Install on your system
3. Generate address
4. Gateway converts to/from regular email
5. Use through Tor for anonymity
```

**Best For:**
- Advanced users
- Multiple email addresses
- High security requirements

### 3.4. Mail2Tor

**Access:** Tor only

**Features:**
- Free anonymous email
- Webmail interface
- No registration required
- Simple and fast

**Comparison Summary:**

| Service | Encryption | Ease of Use | Best For |
|---------|------------|-------------|----------|
| ProtonMail | End-to-end | Easy | General use |
| TorBox | Server-side | Very Easy | Quick setup |
| Bitmessage | Decentralized | Complex | Advanced users |
| Mail2Tor | Basic | Very Easy | Temporary use |

## 4. Forums and Social Networks

### 4.1. Galaxy 2

**Type:** Social Network / Forum

**Features:**
```
├─ Activity feed ("Wire")
├─ Groups functionality
├─ Blogs section
├─ User profiles
├─ Clean interface
└─ No malicious content
```

**Usage:**
1. Create account or browse as guest
2. Join groups by interest
3. Post to activity feed
4. Read blogs
5. Connect with others

**Why Recommended:**
- Well-moderated
- Active community
- No illegal content
- Good for learning

### 4.2. ChatTor

**Type:** Anonymous Chat

**Features:**
- No registration
- Enter any name
- Join public lobbies
- Real-time chat

**Usage:**
1. Visit "onion" address
2. Enter random username
3. Join lobby
4. Start chatting

**Warning:** Do not trust anyone in chat rooms

### 4.3. Facebook (Onion Mirror)

**Type:** Social Network (Onion Version)

**Features:**
- Official Facebook "onion" site
- Claims no logging
- Same interface as clear web

**Security Note:**
- Facebook's terms don't specifically address Tor usage
- Use at your own discretion
- Consider using separate account

### 4.4. Intel Exchange

**Type:** Discussion Forum

**Sections:**
```
├─ Suppressed Technology
│  ├─ Free energy
│  ├─ Anti-gravity
│  └─ Advanced tech
├─ Conspiracy Theories
├─ Science & Research
└─ General Discussion
```

**Why Recommended:**
- Organized categories
- Serious discussions
- Intellectual content
- No random spam

## 5. Encrypted Chat Rooms

### 5.1. CryptoDog

**Type:** Private Encrypted Chat

**Key Features:**
- End-to-end encryption
- No registration required
- Private chat rooms
- Lobby for meeting people

**Setting Up a Private Room:**
```
1. Enable JavaScript (required for encryption)
2. Enter conversation name:
   - Use complex name: "test-chat-room-8976"
   - Must be unique
   - Share only with intended participants
3. Enter nickname
4. Click "Connect"
5. Share conversation name with others
6. Others join using same name
```

**Security Features:**
- Encrypted keys displayed
- Desktop notifications (optional)
- Audio notifications (optional)
- Light/dark mode

**Lobby Access:**
- Conversation name: `lobby`
- Public chat area
- Meet random people
- Less secure than private rooms

### 5.2. Daniel's Chat

**Type:** Traditional IRC-style Chat

**Setup:**
```
1. Visit "onion" address
2. Create username
3. Set password
4. Complete CAPTCHA
5. Select color
6. Enter chat
```

**Features:**
- 120-second waiting room (anti-bot)
- Multiple chat channels
- Direct messaging
- File attachments
- User list display

**Usage:**
```
Message Bar:
├─ Send to: All chatters / Specific users / Offline
├─ Multi-line support
├─ File attachments
└─ Color-coded users
```

## 6. Hidden Wiki

### 6.1. What is the Hidden Wiki?

The Hidden Wiki is a directory of "onion" sites, serving as a starting point for deep web navigation.

**Structure:**
```
Hidden Wiki
├─ Editor's Picks
│  ├─ Recommended starting points
│  └─ Verified safe sites
├─ Introduction Points
│  ├─ Search engines
│  ├─ Financial services
│  └─ Security guides
├─ Financial Services
│  ├─ Bitcoin services
│  ├─ Mixing services
│  └─ Marketplaces
├─ Commercial Services
│  ├─ Hosting
│  ├─ Domains
│  └─ Various products
├─ Email & Messaging
│  ├─ Anonymous email
│  └─ Secure messaging
├─ Social Networks
│  ├─ Forums
│  └─ Social platforms
└─ [Other categories...]
```

### 6.2. Navigating the Hidden Wiki

**Best Practices:**
1. **Start with Editor's Picks** - Verified safe content
2. **Read descriptions** - Understand what each site offers
3. **Check status indicators** - Some sites marked "down"
4. **Use as reference** - Not all links will work
5. **Verify URLs** - Copy carefully, one wrong character = wrong site

**Common Categories:**

| Category | Purpose | Examples |
|----------|---------|----------|
| Introduction Points | Starting resources | Search engines, guides |
| Financial | Money services | Bitcoin, mixing |
| Commercial | Products/Services | Various vendors |
| Domain Services | Hosting/Domains | "onion" hosting |
| Anonymity | Privacy tools | VPNs, proxies |
| Email/Messaging | Communication | Secure email |
| Social | Community | Forums, networks |
| Hosting | File storage | Image hosting |

### 6.3. Important Warnings

⚠️ **Critical Security Notes:**

1. **Dead Links Are Common**
   - Many sites go offline frequently
   - Try multiple mirrors if available

2. **Scams Are Prevalent**
   - Not all listed sites are legitimate
   - Research before using any service

3. **Illegal Content Exists**
   - Some categories contain illegal services
   - Avoid anything questionable
   - Know your local laws

4. **Never Trust Blindly**
   - Verify site authenticity
   - Check community reviews
   - Look for established reputation

## 7. Link Directories

### 7.1. DarkDir (Dark Directory)

**Purpose:** Categorized collection of "onion" links

**Structure:**
```
Categories (Left Sidebar):
├─ Blogs
├─ Social Networks
├─ Libraries & Wikis
├─ Email & Messaging
├─ Financial Services
├─ Anonymity & Security
├─ Hosting & Files
└─ [20+ categories]
```

**Usage:**
1. Select category from left sidebar
2. Wait for page load (may be slow)
3. Review listed sites
4. Click interesting links
5. If site doesn't load, try reloading

**Tips:**
- Many sites won't load (common on deep web)
- Keep reloading or try different mirrors
- Read descriptions before visiting
- Bookmark working sites

## 8. Daily Usage Best Practices

### 8.1. Browsing Habits

**DO:**
- Use bookmarks for trusted sites
- Keep security settings at "Safer" minimum
- Clear cookies/cache regularly
- Use unique usernames per site
- Verify "onion" URLs carefully

**DON'T:**
- Maximize browser window
- Enable JavaScript on unknown sites
- Download files without scanning
- Click random links
- Use real personal information

### 8.2. Communication Security

**Email:**
- Use PGP for sensitive communications
- Separate email per service
- Never use real name

**Chat:**
- Don't share personal details
- Verify identity through multiple channels
- Use private rooms, not public lobbies
- Don't trust anyone implicitly

**Forums:**
- Create unique persona
- Separate accounts per forum
- Don't reveal identifying information
- Use VPN in addition to Tor (optional)

### 8.3. Verification Checklist

Before using any service:
- [ ] Research the site/service
- [ ] Check community reviews
- [ ] Verify "onion" URL from multiple sources
- [ ] Test with disposable email first
- [ ] Never deposit large amounts initially
- [ ] Use escrow when available
